<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-05-08T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-05-08T15:00:00-05:00" n="659" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d659">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">711.428/1949a: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Minister in Canada</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Armour</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-05-08T16:00:00-04:00">May 8,
                                        1936—4 p.m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>41. Department’s instruction No. 267 of March 5, 1936, in regard to
                                Halibut Fishery Convention.</p>
                            <pb facs="0910" n="830" xml:id="pg_830"/>
                            <p>Please inform the Department of any changes in draft which may be
                                desired by the Canadian Government. Department would like to have
                                consideration given to inserting the words “except when such
                                violation is committed in the territorial waters of the other party”
                                in line 16 of Article II after “provisions”. If agreement be reached
                                and it be agreeable to the Canadian Government the Department will
                                request the President to issue full power to you to sign the
                                convention at Ottawa.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>